HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1545
By Hicks G
A RESOLUTION to honor National Police Week and Peace
Officers Memorial Day.
WHEREAS, the preservation of public safety and domestic tranquility depends upon the
enforcement of laws designed to protect life, liberty, and property; and
WHEREAS, this responsibility is entrusted to dedicated law enforcement officers who
serve with courage, integrity, and a steadfast commitment to justice; and
WHEREAS, these officers routinely face danger and adversity, placing themselves in
harm's way to protect the citizens of Tennessee and communities across the United States; and
WHEREAS, many officers have suffered injury, disability, and hardship as a result of
their service, and far too many have made the ultimate sacrifice, giving their lives in the line of
duty; and
WHEREAS, since the first recorded line-of-duty death in 1786, more than 24,500 law
enforcement officers in the United States have lost their lives protecting others, and their names
are forever memorialized as a testament to their bravery and sacrifice; and
WHEREAS, the service and sacrifice of these fallen heroes, including those from
Tennessee, are honored annually during National Police Week, which this year will be observed
May 11-16, 2026; and
WHEREAS, May 15, 2026, will be observed as Peace Officers Memorial Day, a day set
aside to honor all fallen officers and to recognize the enduring sacrifices made by their families;
and
WHEREAS, it is both fitting and proper that we remember and honor those who have
given their lives in service to others and express gratitude to those who continue to serve; now,
therefore,
HJR1545
018290
- 1 -

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor National Police Week during May 11-16, 2026, and Peace
Officers Memorial Day on May 15, 2026, commend the ongoing service of law enforcement
personnel, and pay tribute to the valor, dedication, and enduring legacy of our fallen law
enforcement officers, whose courage will never be forgotten.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
